&gt;	Somehow this seems misguided since there are of course multiple,
&gt;	disconnected internets in the world (e.g., many corporations have
&gt;	their own ethernets running TCP/IP which are not connected to the
&gt;	DARPA Internet).  When these companies start running domain servers,
&gt;	we won't need to suddenly qualify internet addreses by some higher
&gt;	level number which disambiguates among all these disconnected
&gt;	internets.  The idea of course is that a given client only cares about
&gt;	the internet address of a host on the network it is connected to.

Correct me if I am wrong, but aren't internet host addresses
guaranteed to be unique by the registration of net numbers.
We had registered net numbers long before we were on the DARPA internet.

			Kirk Smith
			Purdue Engineering Computer Network
	

